<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="216" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,151,176]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[327,463,153,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="separatus">
<emphasis box="[327,463,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. separatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[610,719,153,176]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eutypus">
<emphasis box="[610,719,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. eutypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having only one small and very shallow atrium (
<figureCitation box="[1303,1423,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1E–F</figureCitation>
), while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[220,334,189,212]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eutypus">
<emphasis box="[220,334,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. eutypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two separate slit-like atria (
<bibRefCitation box="[690,1036,188,213]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" refId="ref7001" refString="Gertsch, W. L. &amp; Davis, L. I. (1940) Report on a collection of spiders from Mexico III. American Museum Novitates, 1069, 1 - 22." type="journal article">Gertsch &amp; Davis 1940: fig. 27</bibRefCitation>
). The female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[1220,1356,189,212]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="separatus">
<emphasis box="[1220,1356,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. separatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez, 2018" authorityName="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez" authorityYear="2018" box="[309,454,224,248]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennimani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[309,454,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. pennimani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[461,551,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[461,551,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez, 2018" authorityName="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez" authorityYear="2018" box="[606,726,224,248]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talquian" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[606,726,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. talquian</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[734,823,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[734,823,223,248]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
by having only one small and very shallow atrium, S1 posterior to CO, and FD that arise from the anterior part of the S1 (
<figureCitation box="[905,1031,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1E–H</figureCitation>
), the carapace that is slightly longer than wide, and the opisthosomal scutum that is narrow and short (
<figureCitation box="[896,1023,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1A, C</figureCitation>
), while 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez, 2018" authorityName="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez" authorityYear="2018" box="[1115,1261,296,320]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pennimani" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1115,1261,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. pennimani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1269,1359,295,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1269,1359,295,320]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez, 2018" authorityName="Chamé-Vázquez &amp; Ibarra-Núñez &amp; Jiménez" authorityYear="2018" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talquian" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. talquian</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[251,341,332,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[251,341,332,357]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
have two large oval atria, the S1 lie ectal to the CD, the FD arise from the posterior part of the S1 (
<figureCitation box="[159,289,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,772,1895]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,769,1898]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Phonotimpus pennimani sp. nov. A, C Epigynum, ventral view; B, D Epigynum, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216348/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 5A–D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[303,389,368,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1929,1951]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,804,1882]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[151,1436,801,1885]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 10. Phonotimpus talquian sp. nov. A, C Epigynum, ventral view; B, D Epigynum, dorsal view (asterisk on internal atrial hood)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216358/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">10A–D</figureCitation>
), the carapace is almost as wide as long, and the opisthosomal scutum is wider and longer (
<figureCitation box="[159,250,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1551,1573]" captionTargetBox="[191,1395,916,1526]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[188,1398,913,1529]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Phonotimpus pennimani sp. nov. A Male habitus, dorsal view; B Male habitus, ventral view; C Female habitus, dorsal view; D Female habitus, ventral view.Scale bars:0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216342/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 2C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[262,298,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1653,1675]" captionTargetBox="[191,1395,1018,1628]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[188,1398,1015,1631]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 7. Phonotimpus talquian sp. nov. A Male habitus, dorsal view; B Male habitus, ventral view; C Female habitus, dorsal view; D Female habitus, ventral view.Scale bars:0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216352/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">7C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="216" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Description.</emphasis>
Female. Carapace, labium, sternum, endites and all legs dull yellow; opisthosoma dusky-yellow, scutum yellowish (
<figureCitation box="[370,503,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1A–D</figureCitation>
). Total length 1.64; carapace 0.68 long, 0.58 wide; opisthosoma 0.96 long, 0.68 wide. Carapace pear-shaped, fovea longitudinal. AER almost straight, 
<collectionCode box="[968,1019,512,535]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:12821" name="City Museum" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">PER</collectionCode>
recurved as seen from above. Eyes sizes and interdistances: AME 0.03, ALE 0.05, PME 0.03, PLE 0.05. AME-AME 0.01, AME-ALE touching, PME-PME 0.04, PME-PLE 0.02, ALE-PLE 0.01. MOA 0.10 long, front width 0.08, back width 0.10. Clypeus height 0.03. Paturon with two frontal spines, mesal one strong, ectal one smaller. Labium slightly wider than long (0.11/0.08), endites longer than wide (0.20/0.13), sternum slightly longer than wide (0.43/0.41). Opisthosoma oval, with dorsal scutum narrow and small, covering 1/3 of the opisthosoma. Leg measurements: I 2.14 (0.59, 0.23, 0.55, 0.50, 0.27), II 1.81 (0.50, 0.22, 0.40, 0.41, 0.28), III 1.67 (0.45, 0.19, 0.31, 0.42, 0.30), IV 2.32 (0.62, 0.21, 0.52, 0.60, 0.37). Leg formula 4123. Leg spination: femur I with 2 prolateral spines in distal half; right tibia I with 6 pairs of ventral spines but left tibia I lacks 1 retroventral spine; metatarsus I with 4 proventral spines and 3 retroventral spines. Femur II with 1 prolateral spine in distal half; tibia II with 5 proventral and 4 retroventral spines; metatarsus II with 4 proventral spines and 2 retroventral spines; left femur IV with one dorso-basal macroseta but right femur IV without such spine; metatarsus III with some distal setae, forming a kind of preening comb. Palpus: femur with one dorso-distal spine, patella with one prolateral spine on its basal half, tibia with one dorso-basal, one dorsodistal and one prolateral-basal spine; with ventral patch of setae on tarsus and small claw. Epigynum: CO opposite one another, sharing single small and shallow atrium (
<figureCitation box="[794,919,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1E–F</figureCitation>
), oval B bigger than S1; egg-shaped S1 lie posterior to CO (
<figureCitation box="[343,479,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1F, 1H</figureCitation>
). In dorsal view, B arise near to CO; FD arise from mesal side of anterior part of S1 (
<figureCitation box="[159,288,1087,1112]" captionStart="FIGURE1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1963,1985]" captionTargetBox="[154,1433,544,1930]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,541,1933]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE1. Female of Phonotimpus separatus. A, C Habitus, dorsal view; B, D Habitus, ventral view; E–H Epigyne, EIntact, ventral view, F Dissected, ventral view, G Dissected, dorsal view, H Dorsal view.Scale bars (A–D):0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216340/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Figs 1G–H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,408,1124,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Taxonomic notes.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[416,733,1124,1149]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" refId="ref7001" refString="Gertsch, W. L. &amp; Davis, L. I. (1940) Report on a collection of spiders from Mexico III. American Museum Novitates, 1069, 1 - 22." type="journal article">Gertsch &amp; Davis (1940: 21)</bibRefCitation>
stated about 
<taxonomicName authority="&quot; The" authorityName="The" box="[886,1089,1124,1149]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="separatus">
<emphasis box="[886,1024,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. separatus</emphasis>
“The
</taxonomicName>
atriobursal orifices are widely separated whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[401,486,1161,1184]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eutypus">
<emphasis box="[401,486,1161,1184]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">eutypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are closely approximated.” The examination of the specimen described here show that they confused the bursae (visible through the integument) with the copulatory openings. They also stated about the 
<collectionCode box="[267,318,1233,1256]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:12821" name="City Museum" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">PER</collectionCode>
in this genus (1940: 20) “In 
<taxonomicName box="[661,801,1233,1256]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="separatus">
<emphasis box="[661,801,1233,1256]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. separatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the median eyes are much nearer the laterals but in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eutypus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. eutypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the four posterior eyes are subequidistantly spaced”, Dr. N. Platnick (who examined both 
<typeStatus box="[1318,1429,1268,1293]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">holotypes</typeStatus>
) informed us that this is also inaccurate, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gertsch &amp; Davis" authorityYear="1940" box="[626,735,1305,1328]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eutypus">
<emphasis box="[626,735,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. eutypus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has the same eye pattern as 
<taxonomicName box="[1057,1193,1305,1328]" class="Arachnida" family="Phrurolithidae" genus="Phonotimpus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="separatus">
<emphasis box="[1057,1193,1305,1328]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">P. separatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1340,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Habitat.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[304,574,1340,1365]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" refId="ref7001" refString="Gertsch, W. L. &amp; Davis, L. I. (1940) Report on a collection of spiders from Mexico III. American Museum Novitates, 1069, 1 - 22." type="journal article">Gertsch &amp; Davis (1940)</bibRefCitation>
did not give information about the habitat. The specimen described here was collected from leaf litter from a secondary vegetation forest, near to maize crops.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="216" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1412,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Distribution.</emphasis>
The female described by 
<bibRefCitation box="[644,914,1412,1437]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" refId="ref7001" refString="Gertsch, W. L. &amp; Davis, L. I. (1940) Report on a collection of spiders from Mexico III. American Museum Novitates, 1069, 1 - 22." type="journal article">Gertsch &amp; Davis (1940)</bibRefCitation>
was found “ 
<quantity box="[1057,1140,1412,1437]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.04672" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" unit="mi" value="5.0">5 miles</quantity>
north Tamazunchale”; the town of Matlapa is located about 
<quantity box="[530,588,1447,1472]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" unit="km" value="8.0">8 km</quantity>
north (
<quantity box="[672,756,1447,1472]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.04672" pageId="3" pageNumber="216" unit="mi" value="5.0">5 miles</quantity>
) of Tamazunchale; therefore, this corresponds to the area of the 
<typeStatus box="[192,240,1485,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation box="[347,430,1484,1509]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1292,1314]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,628,1271]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,628,1271]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distribution map of Phonotimpus spp.: Black square, P. eutypus; Black star, P. separatus; White triangle, P. pennimani sp. nov.; Black circle, P.talquian sp.nov." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1216362/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="216">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
